{"author":{"id":"7c5583353bae3aeeec8f21a625b5a412aebb803ab5a1165d5a45d04ef6f7f00d"},"ops":[{"type":1,"timestamp":1501876762,"nonce":"6I5UmlYLUkNZ+i13t2tIyYNs+cc=","metadata":{"github-id":"MDU6SXNzdWUyNDgxMDMxMTQ=","github-url":"https://github.com/galaxyproject/tools-iuc/issues/1428","origin":"github"},"title":"query_tabular - feature request (or discussion)","message":"I have a two-part feature request for `query_tabular`, assuming that it seems reasonable to you.\n\nAs a simple example, I have a TSV file similar to the following:\n\n| sampleMetadata | class | polarity |\n| :--- | :--- | :--- |\n| blank\\_211 | blank | unknown |\n| blank\\_215 | blank | unknown |\n| blank\\_218 | blank | unknown |\n| blank\\_223 | blank | unknown |\n| blank\\_226 | blank | unknown |\n| pool\\_210 | pool | unknown |\n| pool\\_214 | pool | unknown |\n| pool\\_219 | pool | unknown |\n| pool\\_222 | pool | unknown |\n| Y10\\_212 | y0 | unknown |\n| Y10\\_213 | y0 | unknown |\n| Y10\\_216 | y0 | unknown |\n| Y20\\_217 | y0 | unknown |\n| Y20\\_220 | y0 | unknown |\n| Y20\\_224 | y0 | unknown |\n| Y20\\_225 | y0 | unknown |\n\nTo do so, I run `query_tabular` using the following \\(somewhat contrived\\) parameters to select the blank rows:\n\n| Input Parameter | Value |\n| :--- | :--- |\n| **workdb** | workdb.sqlite |\n| **add\\_to\\_database** | |\n| * Add tables to this Database | |\n| * Tabular Dataset for Table | 3: sampleMetadata.tsv |\n| *input\\_opts:* | |\n| * Filter By | skip |\n| Skip lines | 1 |\n| *tbl\\_opts:* | |\n| * Specify Name for Table | sampleMetadata |\n| * Specify Column Names \\(comma-separated list\\) | sampleMetadata,class,polarity |\n| * Only load the columns you have named into database | False |\n| * Add an auto increment primary key column with this name | Empty. |\n| * This is a unique index | True |\n| * Index on Columns | sampleMetadata |\n| **Save the sqlite database in your history** | False |\n| **SQL Query to generate tabular output** | select \\* from sampleMetadata where sampleMetadata like 'blank\\_%' |\n| **Omit column headers from tabular output** | False |\n\nMy output looks like this:\n\n| #sampleMetadata | class | polarity |\n| :--- | :--- | :--- |\n| blank\\_211 | blank | unknown |\n| blank\\_215 | blank | unknown |\n| blank\\_218 | blank | unknown |\n| blank\\_223 | blank | unknown |\n| blank\\_226 | blank | unknown |\n\nThere are two options that I would have:\n\n1. My output table has a pound sign prepended to the name of the first colum, and I need to use the sed\\_wrapper tool to get rid of it.\n  * **It would be nice to have an option to suppress the generation of this # character to save a workflow step.**\n2. The names for the columns are already present in the first line, but I have to specify them explicitly in the parameter \"Specify Column Names \\(comma-separated list\\)\".\n  * **It would be nice to have an option to extract the column names from the first line.**\n  * This is particularly important for workflows where the column names in the input file that I need to use in the SQL query are unchanging but the column numbers where they appear may change, depending on how previous tools have manipulated columns in the file. \\(For example, Workflow4Metabolomics tools add columns to sampleMetadata and variableMetadata in the course of a workflow.\\)\n   * I am assuming here that some sanity-checking for valid names, or synthesis of valid names, might be necessary for column names that are not valid SQL field names.","files":null}]}